{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 11:04:32.509443", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary\n- Control plane looks up across the Clos fabric (all BGP sessions established and exchanging prefixes), but data plane for web access is abnormal.\n- Client can resolve DNS and ping the web server IP, yet HTTP/TCP connections from client (and other nodes) to webserver0_pod0 fail.\n- Root cause is a misadvertised, more-specific route 10.0.1.0/25 originated by leaf_router_0_0 that hijacks traffic for 10.0.1.0–10.0.1.127 (including 10.0.1.2), sending it to the wrong leaf which cannot deliver it. This explains HTTP failures and inconsistent behavior.\n\nDetection and Evidence\n1) Service reachability tests\n- DNS resolution works:\n  - Client /etc/resolv.conf: nameserver 10.0.0.2\n  - getent/dig from client resolves web0.pod0 to 10.0.1.2.\n- ICMP reachability:\n  - client_0 -> webserver0_pod0 (10.0.1.2) reported 0% loss earlier (rtt ~2.5 ms).\n  - traceroute from client to 10.0.1.2 shows 3 hops through the fabric.\n- HTTP reachability fails from multiple vantage points:\n  - From client_0: curl to http://web0.pod0 and http://10.0.1.2 returns code:000 (no HTTP response).\n  - From dns_pod0 and leaf_router_0_0: curl to 10.0.1.2 also returns code:000.\n  - On webserver0_pod0 itself: service is up and responding locally (curl to 127.0.0.1:80 and 10.0.1.2:80 returns 200 with content).\n  - Web server is listening on 0.0.0.0:80; iptables default ACCEPT.\n\nInterpretation: the application is healthy on the server, but traffic from the fabric is not reaching the process despite ICMP sometimes reaching the host (inconsistency consistent with routing anomaly described below).\n\n2) Control plane (BGP) and routing table inspection\n- All EBGP adjacencies are up across tiers (super-spine, spines, leaves). Examples:\n  - super_spine_router_0: neighbors to both spines up, PfxRcd 3 each.\n  - spines have sessions up to super-spine and both leaves.\n  - leaves have sessions up to both spines.\n- Critical routing anomaly: a more-specific 10.0.1.0/25 is injected by leaf_router_0_0 and learned network-wide.\n  - leaf_router_0_0:\n    - ip addr shows inet 10.0.1.0/25 on loopback (lo). This subnet belongs to the other leaf’s service network, not to this leaf.\n    - show bgp ipv4 unicast shows 10.0.1.0/25 originated locally (best path).\n    - Kernel routing includes 10.0.1.0/24 via spines AND a connected 10.0.1.0/25 via lo (the more-specific wins for 10.0.1.2).\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (the correct owner of 10.0.1.0/24):\n    - has 10.0.1.1/24 on eth2 (correct).\n    - learns 10.0.1.0/25 via BGP from spines (next-hops 172.16.0.6 and 172.16.0.10) and installs it alongside its connected /24. For destinations in 10.0.1.0/25 (e.g., 10.0.1.2), LPM prefers /25, so even the proper leaf would forward those flows away from its local interface.\n  - spines and super-spine:\n    - show ip route 10.0.1.2 selects 10.0.1.0/25 via leaf_router_0_0, not 10.0.1.0/24 via leaf_router_0_1.\n    - Example (super_spine_router_0): “Routing entry for 10.0.1.0/25 … via 172.16.0.1 and 172.16.0.3”.\n- Net effect of the more-specific route:\n  - Traffic for 10.0.1.2 (within 10.0.1.0/25) is steered to leaf_router_0_0, which considers 10.0.1.0/25 as connected on lo and cannot forward to the actual host on leaf_router_0_1. This effectively blackholes TCP/HTTP destined to the server.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 also prefers the received /25 for those addresses and sends them away from its local 10.0.1.0/24, compounding the issue.\n\nLocalization of Faulty Device(s)\n- Primary faulty device: leaf_router_0_0.\n  - Misconfiguration: 10.0.1.0/25 configured on loopback and exported into BGP, creating an unauthorized more-specific covering the first half of leaf_router_0_1’s service subnet.\n\nRoot Cause\n- Route hijack/sinkhole due to an incorrect, more-specific prefix 10.0.1.0/25 originated by leaf_router_0_0. This more-specific advertisement overrides the legitimate aggregate 10.0.1.0/24 from leaf_router_0_1 across the fabric, diverting traffic for 10.0.1.2 to the wrong leaf and preventing HTTP connections from reaching the server process.\n\nAdditional Notes\n- DNS server dns_pod0 is listening on TCP/UDP 53 and answers queries correctly (dig returns 10.0.1.2 for web0.pod0).\n- Web server is healthy locally and listening on 0.0.0.0:80 with no local firewall restrictions.\n- The anomaly specifically impacts addresses in 10.0.1.0–10.0.1.127; addresses in 10.0.1.128/25 would not match the hijacked prefix and would follow the correct /24 route.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 18357, "output_tokens": 9034, "total_tokens": 27391, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 17920}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 7680}}}
